The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       The City Diary
                A 22-year-old woman and her 19-year-old brother allegedly committed suicide on Monday night by jumping in front of a train in Kamardanga, Howrah. Police said both were married. They were allegedly having an affair and were under pressure from relatives to discontinue the relationship. Samapti Laha was married to Asit, 27, of Kamardanga and had a three-year-old child. Asit complained to his wifes grandmother after Samaptis brother, Raju, started visiting his sister regularly. We knew they had a relationship and tried our best to stop them, said the grandmother. According to Asit, Samapti left the house at 9am. At 10.30pm neighbours informed him of the suicides. Rajus wife Anjana, 19, suffered a nervous breakdown after hearing about the incident and had to be hospitalised.     Eastern Railway will run 41 pairs of Puja Special trains between September 30 and November 8, a spokesperson said on Tuesday. These will include nine pairs of Howrah-Delhi bi-weekly superfast trains, four pairs of Howrah-Haridwar weekly superfast express trains, four pairs of Howrah-New Jalpaiguri weekly superfast specials, five pairs of Howrah-New Jalpaiguri weekly air-conditioned superfast specials, four pairs of Howrah-Jaipur weekly AC superfast express trains, five pairs of Sealdah-New Jalpaiguri weekly superfast specials, four pairs of Sealdah-Kathgodam express trains, and six pairs of Malda Town-New Delhi weekly express trains. Booking for these trains started from Tuesday.     The sub-divisional officer of Barrackpore on Tuesday handed over cheques for Rs 1 lakh each to the families of the 13 persons who died in a fire at Readymade Centre on Sodepore Road on May 16. Thirteen people suffocated to death and 20 were injured in the incident.     A fire broke out inside the air-conditioning duct of a seminar hall at Medical College and Hospital at 10am on Tuesday. Parts of the emergency ward were filled with smoke. There were no casualties.     Municipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay ordered the civic health department to intensify its anti-larvae operation in central Calcutta following a sudden rise in the number of malignant malaria cases in the four clinics in Borough VI. The most affected areas include New Market, Mehendi Bagan, Janbazar, Ripon Street, Sudder Street and Free School Street.     A peace protest will be organised on RR Avenue on Wednesday by the All-India Christian Democratic and Backward Peoples Party and the All India Minorities and Weaker Sections Council to protest the killing of Christians and burning of churches in Orissa. The demonstration will start from 11am and continue till 7pm.     An attempt to trim a banyan tree at a construction site in Paikpara was thwarted by residents on Tuesday. They alleged that the site manager had employed men to cut branches of the tree to make way for the construction.            
